.08, "y0": 85.55, "x1": 89.62, "y1": 88.26}], "full_text": "Radiology\n3- Urinary bladder filling defects\nNormal cystogram phase:\n*Contrast filling\nUrinary bladder filling defects\n* no filling defects\n* average capacity\n*Smooth outlines\n*No diverticula\n4- Bladder increased post–voiding residual urine\nWe can see\nNormal post voiding residual urine volume\n-Elevated base - tiny diverticulae\n-wall irregularities, -“fish hook” ureters\n→Benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH)\n3- Pyelography\n• imaging technique in which contrast dye is used to outline renal pelvis and calyces to\nvisualize the collecting system and ureters on X-ray.\n• Contrast can be injected :\n* Antegrade : in same direction of urine\n* Retrograde : in opposite direction of urine\n• Used in case of :\n- non functioning kidney\nanterograde\n- Visualising one side only\nRetrograde\n120"}